post_cb({"13844505": {"ParentId": "13844148", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>Yes, VS is incorrect.  From 5.1.2p7:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_13844148_13844505_0\">[...] for purposes of name lookup, [...] the <em>compound-statement</em> is considered in the context of the <em>lambda-expression</em>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "567292", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "13844505", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2012-12-12T16:45:06.757", "LastActivityDate": "2012-12-12T16:45:06.757"}, "13844148": {"CommentCount": "9", "CreationDate": "2012-12-12T16:27:07.817", "PostTypeId": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "13844505", "LastEditorUserId": "636019", "LastActivityDate": "2012-12-12T22:00:44.930", "LastEditDate": "2012-12-12T22:00:44.930", "ViewCount": "117", "FavoriteCount": "1", "Title": "Are lambas supposed to be able to see local classes?", "Id": "13844148", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>The following gives the error <code>'one': identifier not found</code> in VS2010 and VS2012</p>\n<pre><code>int main()\n{\n    struct one {};\n    [](){ return one(); }();\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>And with a slight tweak...</p>\n<pre><code>int main()\n{\n    struct one {};\n    [](){ one uno; return uno; }();\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>VS2010/VS2012 both have a compiler crash from this code.</p>\n<p>So, the question is (ignoring the compiler crash), are lambas supposed to be able to have visibility of local classes?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><visual-c++><c++11><lambda><visual-studio-2012>", "OwnerUserId": "369872", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_13844148_13844505_0": {"section_id": 5966, "quality": 1.0, "length": 6}}, "n3337": {"so_13844148_13844505_0": {"section_id": 5735, "quality": 1.0, "length": 6}}, "n4659": {"so_13844148_13844505_0": {"section_id": 7460, "quality": 1.0, "length": 6}}}});